     <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-09-02 -->
	 
	 Following a Conversation: Turn-Based vs. Interrupted Threads
	 </font>
     </h2>
    

	<p>
    <div style="clear:both;"></div><h3>Following a Conversation: Turn-Based vs. Interrupted Threads</h3>
<a href="http://www.emacswiki.org/cgi-bin/community?action=browse;id=TurnBasedVsInterruptedThreadMode">CommunityWiki: TurnBasedVsInterruptedThreadMode</a>.&nbsp; Here is a great discussion on how turn-taking or other threading of discussion takes place using Wiki pages.&nbsp; I am very interested about this, for myself, because I want to look at the <a href="http://nfocentrale.net/orcmid/blog/2004/05/federating-wikis-and-overlays.asp">Wiki-Blog-whatnot convergence</a> through common small things, and also see the different ways I can operate nfoWiki as a form of creation of a reference work.&nbsp; The wikipedia experience figures in here, for me.&nbsp; Great material and also some great links.&nbsp; (How one groks the connectivity structure -- site map -- of a wiki is another matter, and also how one might regulate the graph ... hmmm.)<div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em"></div>
    </p>
	<span class="byline">posted by orcmid 
       at <a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2004/05/following-conversation-turn-based-vs.asp">5/15/2004 02:43:00 PM</a></span>
	  
         <!-- 2004-05-10 -->
